	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		I knew what I wanted, and I was going to get it right then and there.  I put forth my paw, only to retract it and hover above another section of humid warmth. <br/><br/>"Buffets are evil." I mumbled to myself as I slapped the last pound of food on my tray.  Scrap had already filled his tray with a vast assortment of food and was in the process of gnawing on a chicken leg and making moves on the waitress - or maybe I had those backwards.<br/>"Two inches." I said as I sat down at Scrap's booth and placed my tray on the badly scratched wooden surface of the table.  "You came within two inches of causing my head to explode today." <br/><br/>Susan's recent phone call echoed loudly in my memory.  Dana had arrived at the office and shuffled around her work area, but did not attempt to access her workstation.  Scrap's little mishap went unnoticed. <br/><br/>Scrap dropped the badly devoured chicken leg on his tray and enjoyed a long drink of his soda.<br/><br/>"I'm sorry, man.  I was in a hurry and wasn't paying attention to what I was putting in my bag.  I'm pretty sure everything else was right where it should have been according to the pictures that we took.  Dude, I even vacuumed her cube!" Scrap lamented.<br/><br/>I stabbed a beef medallion with my fork and used the knife in my other paw to carve off a tender bit of cow goodness.<br/><br/>"I understand, but try to keep in mind that you have to work backwards sometimes.  After the acquisition is complete, you need to press the 'rewind' button on your chimp brain and put everything back exactly where it was - right down to the dust bunnies and dead flies.  Remember what happened at that Spanish wholesale foods company?" I said excitedly. <br/><br/>Scrap pondered my request for a few moments. "Oh, yeah!  Wow, you really messed up that time." <br/><br/>I was shooting Scrap a look of death, but at the same time remembering a serious mistake that I had made at a client location.<br/><br/>[Flashback]<br/><i>We had been brought in several years earlier to image the workstation of an executive at a Spanish wholesale foods company.  The job had encountered several technical challenges that made the job last almost eight hours.  I was fatigued and not thinking clearly.  During the imaging of the executive's workstation, I had adjusted the backrest of his chair to accommodate my frequent stretching.  Unfortunately for this monkey, I forgot to adjust the backrest to its previous location.  When the executive returned to his locked office the following morning and sat in his chair, he knew someone had been in his office.  He became suspicious and confronted the other members of management that had initiated the engagement.  Not a pretty sight. </i><br/>[/flashback]<br/><br/>The blood was rushing from my brain to my stomach, and I knew that I was one doomed monkey.  Unfortunately for me, I wanted to make a first pass run through the image of Dana's workstation before the next day.  <br/><br/>Time to hit Starbucks.<br/><br/>An hour later I was seated in my lab at my secret jungle lair and examining a copy of Dana's workstation image.  The original image (in addition to yet another copy of the image) was safely wrapped in an anti-static bag, tucked away inside a chain of custody bag.   AccessData's Forensic Toolkit was making short work of the data on the image and soon greeted me with a plethora of data adventures to begin.  <br/><br/>The workstation had two user accounts: Administrator and Accounting.  A cursory inspection of Administrator's home directory showed nothing of interest.  The account had not been used to log into the machine in over a year.  <br/><br/>Accounting's home directory was where the action was.  <br/><br/>I knew that MMM used a popular accounting package and Microsoft Office documents to manage the finances.  I knew that this accounting package had a proprietary database structure and that I would have to install the accounting software on a test machine to look at the data.  Lucky for me I had grabbed the retail box of this software while at MMM for just that purpose.<br/><br/>After an installation procedure that never seemed to end and a quick database restore, I double-clicked the accounting software's launch icon and was greeted by a login screen.  <br/><br/>"Hmmm." I thought to myself.  I hadn't had the foresight to remember to ask Susan for authentication information for the accounting software.  <br/><br/>I knew that the default administrator user in the software was 'admin', and according to the documentation in the software's retail box, the default password was 'password'.<br/><br/>No way it could be this easy.<br/><br/>A-d-m-i-n.  P-a-s-s-w-o-r-d.<br/><br/><i>I was in</i>.<br/><br/>A quick scan of available user accounts showed several users: Admin, suze, mmm and dana.  There was user information provided for 'suze' and 'dana' linking those accounts to Susan and Dana.  The Admin info fields were factory default.  The user 'mmm' appeared to have been created by Mike shortly after the software was installed.  I made meticulous notes of these facts on my notepad.<br/><br/>I stumbled through option screen after option screen until I came to something that looked promising.  Under a tab marked "History" I found an option labeled "Transaction History".   I ran a transaction history report, but unfortunately no user information was assigned to each transaction.  <br/><br/>How was I going to know which user put in which transaction?  <br/><br/>A quick (and expensive) call to the software's help desk proved futile.  Nobody had ever asked for such a feature.  Great.<br/><br/>It was getting late and my eyes were starting to close on their own.  The coffee pot was empty.  I was not happy.<br/><br/>My monkey butt was three inches off of the surface of my office chair when an idea popped into my head.<br/><br/>Could FTK read the proprietary database format?<br/><br/>After a few mouse clicks, FTK revealed a startling fact to me.  The database format appeared to be some sort of fixed-length plain-text hack.  FTK screamed through the database.  After several searches on the 'questionable' vendor names that Barbara had noted in her report, I noticed a pattern immediately.<br/><br/>All of the entries were entered by 'mmm'.<br/><hr><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141/http://www.numly.com/numly/verify.asp?id=78447-060516-701607-49"><img alt="esn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141im_/http://numly.com/numly/icon.asp?id=7844706051670160749" border="0"> 78447-060516-701607-49</a> Rate content: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141/http://numly.com/numly/verify.asp?id=7844706051670160749&amp;rate=yes"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141im_/http://numly.com/numly/thumbup.gif" border="0"></a><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141/http://numly.com/numly/verify.asp?id=7844706051670160749&amp;rate=no"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141im_/http://numly.com/numly/thumbdown.gif" border="0"></a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707131141im_/http://numly.com/numly/barcode.asp?code=7844706051670160749&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"><br><br>© 2006 All Rights Reserved.</p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
